"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011450","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-29","<p>Expenditure on maintenance and major repairs by private registered providers of social housing was £5.1 billion in 2014, £5.2 billion in 2015 and £5.1 billion in 2016.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-11-29T16:24:39.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011450/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011450/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-11-21","Social Rented Housing: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answers of 20 November 2018 to Questions 190336 and 190337, what estimate he has made of the expenditure by private registered providers of social housing on maintenance and repairs in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","194028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011451","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-29","<p>No estimate has been made of cost to the National Health Service of emissions from incinerators.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England’s position is that well run and regulated modern municipal waste incinerators are not a significant risk to public health. This is because modern, well managed incinerators make only a small contribution to local concentrations of air pollutants. It is possible that such small additions could have an impact on health but such effects, if they exist, are likely to be very small and not detectable.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-29T14:14:31.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011451/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011451/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-21","Incinerators: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate the Chief Medical Officer has made of the cost to the NHS of emissions from waste incinerators.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","194029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011452","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-29","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has not made an assessment of the financial cost to society of emissions from waste incinerators. PHE’s position is that well run and regulated modern municipal waste incinerators are not a significant risk to public health.</p><p> </p><p>Waste management facilities are regulated in England by the Environment Agency (EA) under the Environmental Permitting (England and Wales) Regulations 2010. When consulted, PHE provides an expert and independent opinion to the regulator (EA) on the potential impacts on human health of emissions arising from existing or proposed regulated facilities. PHE will comment on the applicants’ risk assessments and how they demonstrate the installation’s impacts on human health, and when requested, any additional modelling and assessments conducted by the EA, providing health advice that is clear, concise and based on best available evidence and expert judgement.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","194037","2018-11-29T14:13:49.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011452/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011452/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-11-21","Incinerators: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether Public Health England has made an assessment of the financial cost to society of emissions from waste incinerators.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","194030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011454","Treasury","false","2018-11-29","<p>The Border Delivery Group is actively seeking agreement for communication with stakeholders about border issues to be carried out without non-disclosure agreements as soon as possible.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-29T17:22:14.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011454/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011454/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-21","Borders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will lift the non-disclosure agreements that apply to the Border Delivery Group to enable that Group to update businesses on its contingency plans for after 29 March 2019 in the event of the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","193996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011455","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-26","<p>Neither the Department, nor HS2 Ltd, anticipate that the local government reorganisation in Buckinghamshire will have any significant impact on the efficiency of (i) local community protection by Buckinghamshire local authorities, in relation to HS2, or (ii) interaction between those authorities and HS2 Ltd.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and HS2 Ltd work closely with all Buckinghamshire local authorities and have regular meetings at all levels. As the detail emerges of how the local structures and ways of working are likely to change, these discussions will continue as necessary to maintain smooth interactions.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-11-26T14:40:23.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011455/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011455/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-11-21","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Buckinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what risk assessments have been made by (a) his Department and (b) HS2 Ltd on the effect of local government reorganisation in Buckinghamshire on the efficiency of (i) local community protection by Buckinghamshire local authorities and (ii) interaction between those authorities and HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","193994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011457","Treasury","false","2018-11-26","<p>Under Article 143 of the draft Withdrawal Agreement, the UK will continue to stand behind a share of the EU’s contingent liabilities related to financial operations up to the date of withdrawal. These contingent liabilities are reported to Parliament in the Consolidated Fund accounts as having a remote probability of crystallising. The UK will also get a share of the associated pre-paid guarantee funds and reflows from the financial operations and, in the event of a contingent liability being triggered, the UK will receive its share of any subsequent amounts recovered by the EU.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-11-26T14:49:47.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011457/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011457/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-11-21","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the level of financial liabilities that would arise pursuant to the provisions of Article 143 of the draft Withdrawal Agreement with the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","194063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011459","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-29","<p>The Government will shortly launch its consultation on the introduction of a deposit return scheme (DRS) in England. An impact assessment will be published alongside the consultation, which assesses the social and economic costs and benefits of introducing a DRS, including the impact that a DRS will have on small retailers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Consideration for small retailers will be included in our consultation. We will also take into account the wider effects of a DRS on the retail sector when we consult.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","194132 ; 194133 ; 194134","2018-11-29T16:59:29.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011459/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1011459/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-11-21","Beverage Containers: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Government has estimated the cost of introducing a deposit return scheme for single-use drinks containers.","false","Biography information for Mark Pawsey","Rugby","Mark Pawsey","194131"
